  "text": "Observing Fig. 7 , we see the system responses for some configurations when the input signal is a low frequency square wave (similarly to input step voltage). In this figure, we clearly observe that the frequencies are lower than frequencies of system response in initial configuration. Also, we observe that the input square wave is presented with effects of RL circuit, due to passive probe of oscilloscope be in parallel to primary coil [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . When the frequency is increased, the same effect of sum of responses to each rise and fall of the square wave defined in Equation (1) is observed, as shown in Fig. 8 . In the same way, when the relation f r = f s /n is verified, the output voltage reaches the maximum value, although this response is not a perfect sine wave. However, in accordance to Equations (1) and (2), when the relation f r = f s is verified, the resonance occurs, and the output reaches the maximum value with a perfect sine wave.",
